Your idea is correct, but from the notebook image there are a few Java syntax mistakes.

For addition and subtraction using lambda expressions, the code should be:

Java
interface Add {
    int add(int a, int b);
}

interface Sub {
    int sub(int a, int b);
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Add addition = (a, b) -> a + b;
        System.out.println("Addition = " + addition.add(10, 20));

        Sub subtraction = (a, b) -> a - b;
        System.out.println("Subtraction = " + subtraction.sub(20, 10));
    }
}
Output
Addition = 30
Subtraction = 10
Mistakes I can see in your notebook:

Static void main → should be static void main

S.O.P is fine as shorthand in notes, but in code write:

Java
System.out.println(...)

For subtraction:

Java
(a,b) -> a-b

is correct.

Make sure the interface method and lambda return type are both int.

Even simpler (if your teacher asks only one interface)
Java
interface Operation {
    int calculate(int a, int b);
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {

        Operation add = (a,b) -> a+b;
        Operation sub = (a,b) -> a-b;

        System.out.println(add.calculate(10,20));
        System.out.println(sub.calculate(20,10));
    }
}

This is the form most commonly written in exams and practicals.

